<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910315-0020</DOCNO><DOCID>910315-0020.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Ann Taylor Holdings Inc.:   Retailer Considers Making   An Initial Public Offering</HL><DATE>03/15/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C19</SO><CO>   X.ANN</CO><IN>INITIAL STOCK OFFERINGS (INI)STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)SPECIALTY APPAREL RETAILERS (SAP)SPECIALTY RETAILERS (RTS)STOCK AND BOND REGISTRATIONS, PRICINGS (REG)</IN><LP>   Two years after it went private in a leveraged buy-out,Ann Taylor Holdings Inc., New York, said it is &quot;considering&quot;an initial public offering of common stock.   The holding company for Ann Taylor Inc., a 176-unitwomen's retail chain, said that it is mailing a notice of theproposed offering to holders of Ann Taylor's 13.5 millionwarrants outstanding, as required before filing aregistration statement with the Securities and ExchangeCommission. Ann Taylor Chairman Joseph E. Brooks declinedfurther comment.</LP><TEXT>   By going public, Ann Taylor -- which posted a $1.1 millionprofit in fiscal 1990 compared with a net loss of $11.2million in 1989 -- would take advantage of its currenthealthy sales and the strong equity market and would alsohelp pay down its $372 million in debt, said one bondanalyst.   Ann Taylor was purchased from Campeau Corp. in February1989 by Merrill Lynch Capital Partners and Mr. Brooks, theformer chairman and chief executive of Lord andamp; Taylor. Sincethe acquisition, the company has added 57 stores and raised$190 million in two junk bond offerings.</TEXT></DOC>